"But in spite of the severe financial difficulties in which the Company became involved for some years, the Metro- politan Railway Company steadily pushed forward. Those who guided its destinies had a great ideal before them. It was to lay down an underground ring round Inner London. The Thames in those days was an insuperable barrier to underground engineering, for the “cut and cover” principle is obviously inapplicable to water. The original Metropulitan was a highly important section of the ring, and the scheme was to extend at both ends as rapidly as possible. But those were the days when unlimited cut-throat competition was held to be the golden principle of economic success and national well-being, and other promoters were framing and launching schemes to be able to build their independent bits of railway so as to command good terms if the others proved stronger than they. And so, while the Metropolitan was devoting its chief energies"